prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
At the redshifts of our proposed galaxies, the CO(2-1) line is shifted to 222-224 GHz, accessible with a single sideband for one tuning of ALMA band 6. We have estimated CO(2-1) fluxes based on measured HI masses, by assuming a conservative H2/HI ratio of 0.05 (see, e.g., Lagos et al. 2011), a brightness temperature ratio of r_21 = 1.0 (typical for most local galaxies) and a metallicity-dependent CO/H2 conversion factor (following Genzel et al. 2010).
We estimate that our sources will have typical line flux densities of 20-100 mJy. At the distance of our sample, we estimate that we will be sensitive to CO luminosities down to ~3.5e6 K km/s pc^2 (which, assuming typical CO/H2 conversion factors, corresponds to a few times 10^7 solar masses of molecular gas).
Our proposed sensitivity limit of 5 mJy is designed to obtain good quality detections in the case that the molecular gas mass is lower than our HI mass-based prediction. In the case of a non-detection, the requested sensitivity will be sufficient to provide scientifically useful upper limits. We have requested three relatively large basebands, 1875MHz, spaced in order to maximise coverage of the sideband.
TECHNICAL NOTE: For the purposes of the ALMA OT, all sources have been set to 0 km/s velocity (giving each source an individual velocity causes the OT to fail to process the project). We have selected our sample to fall within a narrow spectral range: all sources will have the CO(2-1) line fall within the range 222-224 GHz. We have requested 3 basebands, to cover the approximate frequency range 220-225 GHz. This will ensure all lines fall within the sideband (also accounting for the Doppler motion of the Earth), avoiding the edges of the bands.
The total observing time calculated by the OT is 36.5 minutes.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to observe the 12CO(2-1) emission line in 46 low-stellar mass galaxies in the local Universe, which span a large range (0.5 dex) in gas phase metallicity. Modern surveys for atomic gas have revealed a strong inverse correlation between Hi content and gas-phase metallicity, providing strong constraints for galaxy evolution models (see Bothwell et al. 2013). The paucity (and limited metallicity/stellar mass range) of existing CO datasets prevent investigation of any trends between metallicity and molecular gas content. Our proposed sample of 46 low mass, low metallicity galaxies will provide superb statistics of molecular gas content across a metallicity range currently untouched by any large survey. Our program, involving a significant number of low metallicity systems (with challengingly large CO/H2 conversion factors) is only possible with the sensitivity of ALMA.
